pression in conversational anecdotes and stories that deal with pressing issues: the flight from the inner city, crime in the streets, working conditions in the steel mills, the maintenance of ethnic identity, the place of blacks in a predominantly white society. The folklore reveals strongly held attitudes such as the loathing of industrial work, resistance to assimilation, and black adoption of middle-class-white values. Miliworkers and mill executives, housewives, ethnic performers, storekeepers, and preachers tell their stories about the Region. The concerns that occupy them affect city dwellers throughout the United States. Land of the Millrats, though it depicts a special place, speaks for much of America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBräuche, Etikette, Folklore. 0aBräuche, Etikette, Folklore. 0aManners and customs. 0aVolkskultur. 4aFolklore -- Calumet Region (Ill. and Ind.). 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology. 4aUrban folklore -- Calumet Region (Ill. and Ind.). 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Midwest (IA, IL, IN, KS, MI, MN, MO, ND, NE, OH, SD, WI).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Social Science eBook Packagez9783110353556oZDB-23-HCI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441922340uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441923040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674419230.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKA